  "prompt": "How does the federal reserve count money?",
  "response": "The Federal Reserve tracks money supply using several measures, primarily:\n\n1. M0 (Monetary Base)\n- Physical currency in circulation\n- Coins and paper money\n- Bank reserves held at Federal Reserve\n\n2. M1\n- Includes M0\n- Adds demand deposits\n- Checking account balances\n- Traveler's checks\n\n3. M2\n- Includes M1\n- Adds savings deposits\n- Money market accounts\n- Small-denomination time deposits\n\n4. M3 (less commonly used now)\n- Includes M2\n- Adds larger time deposits\n- Institutional money market funds\n\nThese measures are calculated by tracking:\n- Currency printed and in circulation\n- Bank deposits\n- Electronic transactions\n- Account balances\n- Monetary transactions\n\nThe Fed uses these measures to:\n- Monitor economic conditions\n- Assess money supply\n- Make monetary policy decisions\n- Control inflation\n- Manage economic growth\n\nThey collect data from banks, financial institutions, and government reporting systems to compile these money supply measurements.",
